1
00:00:00,005 --> 00:00:01,006
- [Instructor] Today, we're going to learn

2
00:00:01,006 --> 00:00:05,000
about event handling in JavaScript.

3
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,003
Event handling allows us to listen for and respond

4
00:00:07,003 --> 00:00:11,009
to user actions like clicks, drags and more.

5
00:00:11,009 --> 00:00:16,003
This is a key part of making our webpage interactive.

6
00:00:16,003 --> 00:00:18,006
In this lesson, we'll add event listeners

7
00:00:18,006 --> 00:00:21,004
to our plant elements to handle the drag event.

8
00:00:21,004 --> 00:00:25,001
we'll update our script.js file to listen for when the user

9
00:00:25,001 --> 00:00:28,006
clicks on a plant element and starts dragging it.

10
00:00:28,006 --> 00:00:32,003
Before we continue on, let's talk about event listeners.

11
00:00:32,003 --> 00:00:33,006
Event listeners are functions

12
00:00:33,006 --> 00:00:36,006
that wait for specific events to occur,

13
00:00:36,006 --> 00:00:38,006
and then execute a predefined code

14
00:00:38,006 --> 00:00:41,008
in response to those events.


15
00:00:41,008 --> 00:00:45,009
Let's break down some key components of event listeners.

16
00:00:45,009 --> 00:00:48,008
First, there's event types.

17
00:00:48,008 --> 00:00:51,006
Events in JavaScript can be triggered by user interactions

18
00:00:51,006 --> 00:00:54,000
like clicks or key presses,

19
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:58,003
or even changes in the document, like resizing.

20
00:00:58,003 --> 00:01:00,008
Next, there's targets.

21
00:01:00,008 --> 00:01:02,002
Every event is associated

22
00:01:02,002 --> 00:01:06,000
with a particular element in the DOM.

23
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,001
We call this the event target.

24
00:01:08,001 --> 00:01:10,007
For example, if you click on a button,

25
00:01:10,007 --> 00:01:15,001
the button is the event target for the click event.


26
00:01:15,001 --> 00:01:17,009
Next is the event handler function.

27
00:01:17,009 --> 00:01:19,007
It contains code that should be executed

28
00:01:19,007 --> 00:01:24,000
when that particular event occurs.

29
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:26,007
Another crucial step in event handling

30
00:01:26,007 --> 00:01:30,000
is adding the event listener.

31
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:31,006
And this process really is about attaching

32
00:01:31,006 --> 00:01:36,006
an event listener to a particular element.

33
00:01:36,006 --> 00:01:39,001
In our code, we'll add an event listener

34
00:01:39,001 --> 00:01:42,004
for the pointer down event.

35
00:01:42,004 --> 00:01:45,001
This event is triggered when the user presses

36
00:01:45,001 --> 00:01:49,000
a pointer button like a mouse click on the element.


37
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:51,007
Notice, the onpointerdown property

38
00:01:51,007 --> 00:01:54,004
is set to our pointerDrag function.

39
00:01:54,004 --> 00:01:58,004
This is notated by the equal sign in between the two.

40
00:01:58,004 --> 00:02:01,003
We haven't created our pointerDrag function yet,

41
00:02:01,003 --> 00:02:03,001
but we'll do that next.

42
00:02:03,001 --> 00:02:07,000
What pointerDrag will do will handle the initial actions

43
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:09,008
when the user starts dragging the element.

44
00:02:09,008 --> 00:02:14,000
So, let's go ahead and add it now.

45
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:17,000
Our pointerDrag function is ready to go.

46
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:17,008
The pointerDrag function

47
00:02:17,008 --> 00:02:22,002
takes an event object (e) as its parameter.


48
00:02:22,002 --> 00:02:24,003
The e.preventDefault method

49
00:02:24,003 --> 00:02:26,008
prevents any default actions that might occur

50
00:02:26,008 --> 00:02:29,002
when the event is triggered.

51
00:02:29,002 --> 00:02:32,000
The console.log statement logs the event object

52
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:36,006
to the console, which is useful for debugging.

53
00:02:36,006 --> 00:02:40,004
Let's break this function down even further.

54
00:02:40,004 --> 00:02:43,008
First, let's talk about the parameter (e).

55
00:02:43,008 --> 00:02:47,003
This parameter represents the event object.

56
00:02:47,003 --> 00:02:49,002
It contains information about the event

57
00:02:49,002 --> 00:02:51,002
that triggered the function.


58
00:02:51,002 --> 00:02:55,007
In this case, the event is a pointer or mouse press.

59
00:02:55,007 --> 00:02:58,007
You're probably wondering, what's an object?

60
00:02:58,007 --> 00:03:00,007
Objects allow you to store multiple values

61
00:03:00,007 --> 00:03:03,004
in a single variable.

62
00:03:03,004 --> 00:03:06,002
Each are identified by a unique key

63
00:03:06,002 --> 00:03:09,006
and come in a collection of key value pairs.

64
00:03:09,006 --> 00:03:11,007
Objects are used to model and represent

65
00:03:11,007 --> 00:03:15,000
real world entities and their properties,

66
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:19,004
making it easier to manage and manipulate related data.

67
00:03:19,004 --> 00:03:22,003
Another key point about objects,

68
00:03:22,003 --> 00:03:25,000
especially as they relate to events,

69
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:29,000
is that objects come with predefined functions,

70
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:31,007
also maybe known as methods.


71
00:03:31,007 --> 00:03:36,006
Objects also come with methods or functions.

72
00:03:36,006 --> 00:03:38,003
And functions when they relate to objects

73
00:03:38,003 --> 00:03:42,002
have a specific mission and goal.

74
00:03:42,002 --> 00:03:44,000
For example, we've been working

75
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:47,002
with document.getElementById.

76
00:03:47,002 --> 00:03:51,000
getElementByIdwhich is part of the document object

77
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:55,008
looks in the DOM for an element of a particular ID,

78
00:03:55,008 --> 00:03:57,008
in the case of our plants.

79
00:03:57,008 --> 00:04:02,003
That brings us to the e.preventDefault line.

80
00:04:02,003 --> 00:04:05,003
This line prevents the default behavior of the event.


81
00:04:05,003 --> 00:04:08,002
For instance, when you click and drag an image,

82
00:04:08,002 --> 00:04:12,001
the browser might try to drag the image as a default action.

83
00:04:12,001 --> 00:04:13,002
We don't want that to happen,

84
00:04:13,002 --> 00:04:16,005
so we use this line to stop it.

85
00:04:16,005 --> 00:04:19,004
Next, we log the event.

86
00:04:19,004 --> 00:04:22,002
This logs the event object to the console.

87
00:04:22,002 --> 00:04:25,002
The console is a tool built in the browsers

88
00:04:25,002 --> 00:04:27,002
that allows developers to see information

89
00:04:27,002 --> 00:04:29,004
about their code as it runs.

90
00:04:29,004 --> 00:04:33,000
You might have seen a little bit of this in the CSS chapter.

91
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:36,007
By logging e, we can see details about the pointer event,

92
00:04:36,007 --> 00:04:39,000
which is useful for debugging and understanding

93
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:42,000
what's happening when the function is triggered.


94
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,002
We'll see this in action shortly.

95
00:04:44,002 --> 00:04:48,002
Next, we're using the pos3 and the pos4 variables

96
00:04:48,002 --> 00:04:51,000
that we defined earlier.

97
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,000
Remember, pos3 and the pos4

98
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:59,007
store the current cursor position on the X and Y axis.

99
00:04:59,007 --> 00:05:02,000
Summing up what these lines do,

100
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,005
they store the initial position of the mouse cursor.

101
00:05:05,005 --> 00:05:10,000
So, e.clientX gives a horizontal coordinate

102
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:13,002
on the X axis of the mouse pointer.


103
00:05:13,002 --> 00:05:18,009
And e.clientY gives a vertical coordinate or on the Y axis.

104
00:05:18,009 --> 00:05:21,009
This all happens when the event occurs.

105
00:05:21,009 --> 00:05:23,009
We save them in our variables

106
00:05:23,009 --> 00:05:27,009
and this helps us calculate how far the cursor moves.

107
00:05:27,009 --> 00:05:30,004
Finally, in these last two lines,

108
00:05:30,004 --> 00:05:34,000
we're setting up event listeners for dragging.

109
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:35,002
The first one,

110
00:05:35,002 --> 00:05:39,004
onpointermove means that while the pointer is moving,

111
00:05:39,004 --> 00:05:43,004
the element drag function will be called continuously.

112
00:05:43,004 --> 00:05:45,000
This function will handle updating

113
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:48,004
the position of the elements as you drag it.


114
00:05:48,004 --> 00:05:51,007
The way that document.onpointerup works

115
00:05:51,007 --> 00:05:54,004
is that when you release the pointer button,

116
00:05:54,004 --> 00:05:58,002
the stopElementDrag function will be called.

117
00:05:58,002 --> 00:06:01,007
And this function will stop the dragging process.

118
00:06:01,007 --> 00:06:03,004
We haven't written these functions yet,

119
00:06:03,004 --> 00:06:08,007
so let's go ahead and do that.

120
00:06:08,007 --> 00:06:10,007
Let's break down what these two functions,

121
00:06:10,007 --> 00:06:14,000
elementDrag and stopElementDrag do.

122
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:17,000
elementDrag is responsible for updating the position

123
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,007
of the terrariumElement as a user drags it.


124
00:06:20,007 --> 00:06:25,000
First, it calculates the new cursor position.

125
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:26,007
The math here that you're seeing

126
00:06:26,007 --> 00:06:29,004
represents how much the mouse has moved

127
00:06:29,004 --> 00:06:32,004
since the last mouse move event.

128
00:06:32,004 --> 00:06:34,009
And then in the next two lines,

129
00:06:34,009 --> 00:06:38,009
we update the stored cursor position.

130
00:06:38,009 --> 00:06:43,000
The next two lines are responsible for moving the element.

131
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:49,004
And here, we're actually manipulating the DOM through CSS.

132
00:06:49,004 --> 00:06:53,002
terrariumElement.style.top sets the top position

133
00:06:53,002 --> 00:06:56,004
of the element by adjusting its current top position

134
00:06:56,004 --> 00:07:00,002
by the amount the mouse has moved vertically.


135
00:07:00,002 --> 00:07:03,007
terrariumElement.style.left does the same thing

136
00:07:03,007 --> 00:07:06,002
except on the left position.

137
00:07:06,002 --> 00:07:09,002
So it adjusts its current left position

138
00:07:09,002 --> 00:07:13,002
by the amount the mouse has moved horizontally.

139
00:07:13,002 --> 00:07:15,004
And all this really here is doing

140
00:07:15,004 --> 00:07:19,004
is moving the element to follow the mouse movement.

141
00:07:19,004 --> 00:07:21,005
So, every time you drag a plant,

142
00:07:21,005 --> 00:07:24,004
it follows your mouse cursor.

143
00:07:24,004 --> 00:07:26,007
Let's talk about stopElementDrag.

144
00:07:26,007 --> 00:07:29,007
This function is responsible for stopping

145
00:07:29,007 --> 00:07:33,007
the drag operation when the user releases the mouse button.


146
00:07:33,007 --> 00:07:37,002
onpointerup = null removes the event listener

147
00:07:37,002 --> 00:07:39,007
for the pointer up event.

148
00:07:39,007 --> 00:07:40,007
And what this really means

149
00:07:40,007 --> 00:07:42,004
is that the stopElementDrag function

150
00:07:42,004 --> 00:07:47,002
will no longer be called when the mouse button is released.

151
00:07:47,002 --> 00:07:49,002
Same thing for onpointermove.

152
00:07:49,002 --> 00:07:52,009
It removes the event listener for the pointermove event

153
00:07:52,009 --> 00:07:55,007
so that the elementDrag function will no longer be called

154
00:07:55,007 --> 00:07:57,007
when the mouse moves.

155
00:07:57,007 --> 00:08:00,004
All this really means here is that the element

156
00:08:00,004 --> 00:08:02,002
will stay in its new position,

157
00:08:02,002 --> 00:08:05,004
and no further updates to its position will be made

158
00:08:05,004 --> 00:08:09,002
until a new drag operation is initiated.


159
00:08:09,002 --> 00:08:11,004
And that's it for this lesson.

160
00:08:11,004 --> 00:08:15,000
If we go ahead and try and run our terrarium,

161
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:20,000
what we'll find is that things don't work quite yet,

162
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:21,005
and that's okay.

163
00:08:21,005 --> 00:08:23,004
We have a couple more steps here

164
00:08:23,004 --> 00:08:27,004
before we make this terrarium come to life.

165
00:08:27,004 --> 00:08:30,000
In this lesson, we learned about event handling

166
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:33,004
and added event listeners to our plant elements.

167
00:08:33,004 --> 00:08:35,005
This allows us to respond to user actions

168
00:08:35,005 --> 00:08:38,003
like clicks and drags.


169
00:08:38,003 --> 00:08:40,001
We spent a lot of time here

170
00:08:40,001 --> 00:08:43,006
and that's because understanding event handling is crucial

171
00:08:43,006 --> 00:08:46,008
for creating interactive webpage.

172
00:08:46,008 --> 00:08:49,001
In the next lesson, we'll talk a little bit more

173
00:08:49,001 --> 00:08:51,001
about things we need to add

174
00:08:51,001 --> 00:08:54,003
to make our terrarium come to life.

175
00:08:54,003 --> 00:08:56,000
And that'll be closures.

176
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:06,000
See you soon.

